# Command helmfile

## What does this command do:

Declaratively deploy your Kubernetes manifests, Kustomize configs, and Charts as Helm releases.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/helmfile/helmfile/releases/download/v1.4.4/helmfile_1.4.4_linux_amd64.tar.gz | tar -xz -C ~/.local/bin/ helmfile && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/helmfile
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/helmfile/helmfile/releases/download/v1.4.4/helmfile_1.4.4_linux_arm64.tar.gz | tar -xz -C ~/.local/bin/ helmfile && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/helmfile
For Mac install using: brew install helmfile

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.local/bin/helmfile
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.local/bin/helmfile
For Mac run: /opt/homebrew/bin/helmfile

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/helmfile/helmfile

## Command options

# Apply all releases (only when there are changes)
helmfile apply

# Sync all releases (always apply)
helmfile sync

# Diff releases against the current cluster state
helmfile diff

# Destroy all releases
helmfile destroy

# List all releases defined in state file
helmfile list

# Show release status
helmfile status

# Template releases (render manifests locally)
helmfile template

# Lint all charts
helmfile lint

# Update chart dependencies
helmfile deps

# Add repositories defined in state file
helmfile repos

# Fetch charts to local directory
helmfile fetch

# Show deployment order (DAG groups)
helmfile show-dag

# Target a specific environment
helmfile -e production sync
helmfile -e staging apply

# Use a specific state file
helmfile -f path/to/helmfile.yaml sync

# Target releases by label selector
helmfile -l app=myapp sync
helmfile -l tier=frontend,tier!=proxy apply

# Run interactively (prompt before changes)
helmfile -i apply

# Run against a specific namespace
helmfile -n mynamespace sync

# Skip repo/dependency updates
helmfile sync --skip-deps

# Debug output
helmfile --debug sync

# Initialize helmfile (install helm + plugins)
helmfile init

# Print environment config
helmfile print-env

# Write rendered values files
helmfile write-values

# Generate shell autocompletion
helmfile completion bash | sudo tee /etc/bash_completion.d/helmfile
helmfile completion zsh > ~/.zsh/completions/_helmfile
